sentences.l:
Of water there is need,
for him who comes to a meal,
of a towel and a warm welcome,
of a kindly disposition,
if he could get it for himself,
of speech and of silence in return.

sentences.t:
Vitz er þǫrf,
þeim er víða ratar;
dælt er heima hvat;
at augabragði verðr,
sá er ekki kann
ok með snotrom sitr.

sentences.l:
Of wit there is need,
for him who travels widely;
everything is easy at home;
he becomes a laughing-stock,
the man who knows nothing
and sits among the wise.

It is not so good,
as it is said to be good,
ale for the sons of men;
for the less a man knows,
the more he drinks,
of his own mind.

The fool gapes,
when he comes visiting,
he mumbles to himself or broods;
it is all at once,
if he gets a drink:
then the man's mind is laid bare.

One should go;
a guest should not be
ever in one place;
the beloved turns loathed,
if he sits long
on another's benches.

With weapons and garments
friends should gladden each other;
that is most seen on oneself;
givers-in-return and repayers
stay friends the longest,
if it is fated to go well.

sentences.t:
Ungr var ek forðom,
fór ek einn saman;
þá varð ek villr vega;
auðigr þóttomz,
er ek annan fann:
maðr er mannz gaman.

sentences.l:
Young I was once,
I fared alone;
then I became lost of my ways;
rich I thought myself,
when I found another:
man is man's delight.

Of little sands,
of little seas,
little are the minds of men;
for all men
did not turn out equally wise;
the world is half everywhere.

Moderately wise
should each of men be,
never let him be too wise;
his fate
let no one know beforehand:
his mind is the most sorrow-free.

Early should rise
he who has few workers,
and go to look to his work;
much holds back
him who sleeps through the morning;
half of wealth is won by the vigorous.
